name: Give notice and get assent for a planned activity on or near a SSSI

components.content:
You should use this form to submit a notice of proposal (assent) to Natural England to undertake activities on or near protected sites, that you have already screened as part of your Section 28G duties. You cannot use this form to report emergency works or works that have already started. 

Check your activities are likely to cause damage before completing this form. If your activities are deemed to likely cause damage to the notified features of a European site, you must complete a habitats regulations assessment (HRA) first, and seek Natural England advice, if applicable. 

Persons who have been contracted by public bodies, known as S28G authorities, may complete this form on their behalf where they have been officially appointed to act. You may need to provide proof of this permission. 



## To help assess the impacts of your activities
Use the [designated sites view system](https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/) to find out which habitats and species are of special scientific interest, and which activities are likely to damage them. 

Search for the relevant SSSI, select 'View details' then 'View ORNECs'.

components.content:
This form only provides a submission route to assent proposals for activities from public bodies on protected sites.

### For supplementary forestry operations consent
To submit a supplementary notice of forestry operations within a site of special scientific importance, you need to [use the form available on GOV.UK](https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/supplementary-notice-of-operations-within-an-sssi) and follow the instructions for submission.


### For notice of consent 
To submit a notice of proposal to cause, carry out or permit an operation requiring Natural England's consent on an SSSI, [use this form](ADD LIVE LINK TO CONSENT FORM).

You must consider whether the proposal could affect one or more European sites. The effects of your proposal may depend on its location. 

It could be:

* on the site
* near the site
* some distance away, for example by causing air, water or noise pollution or affecting a feeding area used by one of the site’s designated species

[Follow the guidance on protecting European Sites](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/habitats-regulations-assessments-protecting-a-european-site) and considering whether your proposal might affect one.

For each EU site named, you will need to complete a Habitats Regulation Assessment (HRA) and upload those details as part of this notice.

If your activities might effect a European site, you’ll need to carry out a habitats regulations assessment (HRA) first. This assessment is to help you plan how to avoid significant effects or mitigate for them, when you’re carrying out planned activities. You should do this before you seek SSSI assent from Natural England. 

You should follow the [guidance about how to carry out a habitats regulations assessment](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/habitats-regulations-assessments-protecting-a-european-site). 

You should use Natural England’s [European sites conservation advice](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/conservation-objectives-for-land-based-protected-sites-in-england-how-to-use-the-site-advice) and [marine protected areas conservation advice](https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/conservation-advice-packages-for-marine-protected-areas).

pages.title: You need to complete a HRA first

components.content:
As a competent authority you have a duty to help protect, conserve and restore European sites. You must carry out a habitats regulations assessment to decide if the planned activities are likely to affect a European protected site.

You must follow the [guidance about how to carry out a habitats regulations assessment](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/habitats-regulations-assessments-protecting-a-european-site). You should use Natural England’s [European sites conservation advice](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/conservation-objectives-for-land-based-protected-sites-in-england-how-to-use-the-site-advice) and [marine protected areas conservation advice](https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/conservation-advice-packages-for-marine-protected-areas).


See further information on [carrying out Habitats Regulations Assessments before applying for SSSI assent](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/sites-of-special-scientific-interest-public-body-responsibilities#sites-of-international-importance) from Natural England.

Based on the information you have provided, you have concluded that the planned activities are likely to have significant effects on at least one protected European site. 

Before submitting this form, you should consider seeking European Site advice from Natural England (using the ADD link) to help you understand whether an Appropriate Assessment is required and how potential impacts could be avoided or reduced.

An Appropriate Assessment is part of the Habitats Regulations Assessment (HRA) process. 
Natural England’s advice can help you:
* confirm whether likely significant effects have been fully ruled out
* identify suitable avoidance or mitigation measures.

Any mitigation identified may also help prevent damage to the special scientific interest of any SSSI present.

components.content:
You should consult Natural England on your proposed plans to avoid or mitigate significant effects on the European site to complete an Appropriate Assessment. You should consider the advice to help you decide whether all significant effects have been ruled out. The mitigations might also prevent potential damage to the special scientific interest of any SSSI also present.

For guidance on completing HRA assessments, [click here](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/habitats-regulations-assessments-protecting-a-european-site).

For advice relating to Habitats Regulation Assessment, [use this form - Add link]().

It is your responsibility to consider the potential damage on the special habitats, species or geology of SSSI land from activities planned to be carried out. This includes planned activities on land outside the boundaries of an SSSI that are likely to damage the special interest features. 

Find out more about [your responsibility towards SSSIs](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/sites-of-special-scientific-interest-public-body-responsibilities).

You do not need to request Natural England’s assent for activities that you’ve decided are unlikely to damage the European site or its features or the features of special scientific interest of an SSSI.

You should keep a record of proposed activities that you do not seek assent for, and your reasons for this. 

Find out more about [your responsibility towards SSSIs and when to apply for SSSI assent](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/sites-of-special-scientific-interest-public-body-responsibilities) from Natural England.
